<paragraph id="8B8736C39B5BBB22FFE6715774638D00" blockId="117.[112,1225,1306,1648]" box="[114,313,1306,1328]" pageId="117" pageNumber="120">
<subSubSection id="C32265489B5BBB22FFE67157746F8D00" box="[114,309,1306,1328]" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" type="nomenclature">
Pigo (
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FF3F715774748D00" baseAuthorityName="Lacepede" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[171,302,1306,1328]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigus">Rutilus pigus</taxonomicName>
)
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32265489B5BBB22FEA1715774E18E40" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" type="discussion">
, 
<paragraph id="8B8736C39B5BBB22FEAA715774E18E40" blockId="117.[112,1225,1306,1648]" pageId="117" pageNumber="120">
the other 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FE34715777628D00" box="[416,568,1306,1328]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">Rutilus species</taxonomicName>
native to the southern lakes, was recorded in fewer lakes than R. aula (Como, Mezzola, and Maggiore), and was everywhere less abundant than R. aula. 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FC58717671478D60" baseAuthorityName="Lacepede" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[972,1053,1338,1360]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigus">R. pigus</taxonomicName>
was recorded in highest numbers in lakes Como and Mezzola where 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FDE3711677958D40" box="[631,719,1370,1392]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilus">R. rutilus</taxonomicName>
had not become abundant (yet). In Lake Maggiore, only 
<specimenCount id="9D3EFD4A9B5BBB22FF0B713774578DA0" box="[159,269,1402,1424]" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" type="juvenile">six juvenile</specimenCount>
fish phenotypically resembling 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FDDD713677C08DA0" baseAuthorityName="Lacepede" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[585,666,1402,1424]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigus">R. pigus</taxonomicName>
were recorded.Three of these were confirmed as 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FB07713675CF8D80" baseAuthorityName="Lacepede" baseAuthorityYear="1803" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigus">R. pigus</taxonomicName>
by genetic barcoding, while two had the mitochondrial barcode of 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FCBA71D676DD8D80" box="[814,903,1434,1456]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilus">R. rutilus</taxonomicName>
and one had that of R. aula (
<figureCitation id="13032A469B5BBB22FB3771D775EF8DE0" captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="118.[460,516,1278,1295]" captionTargetBox="[458,1566,200,1226]" captionTargetId="figure-8@118.[456,1570,197,1230]" captionTargetPageId="118" captionText="Figure 34a: Rutilus species of the perialpine region. Rutilus aula (triotto) and Rutilus pigus (pigo) are native south of the Alps. Rutilus rutilus (roach) is native to the northern perialpine region and is introduced in many southern perialpine lakes, and invasive in several." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5779641" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5779641/files/figure.png" pageId="117" pageNumber="120">Figure 34</figureCitation>
). In Lake Lugano, no fish phenotypically matched 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FD2571F6765E8DE0" baseAuthorityName="Lacepede" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[689,772,1466,1488]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigus">R. pigus</taxonomicName>
, however 
<specimenCount id="9D3EFD4A9B5BBB22FCFB71F776968DE0" box="[879,972,1466,1488]" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" type="adult">one adult</specimenCount>
fish that was phenotypically mostly 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FF797196741C8DC0" box="[237,326,1498,1520]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilus">R. rutilus</taxonomicName>
had the mitochondrial barcode and also the lateral line scale count of 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FC6A719671158DC0" baseAuthorityName="Lacepede" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[1022,1103,1498,1520]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigus">R. pigus</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="13032A469B5BBB22FBC8719771E68DC0" box="[1116,1212,1498,1520]" captionStart="Figure 34" captionStartId="118.[460,516,1278,1295]" captionTargetBox="[458,1566,200,1226]" captionTargetId="figure-8@118.[456,1570,197,1230]" captionTargetPageId="118" captionText="Figure 34a: Rutilus species of the perialpine region. Rutilus aula (triotto) and Rutilus pigus (pigo) are native south of the Alps. Rutilus rutilus (roach) is native to the northern perialpine region and is introduced in many southern perialpine lakes, and invasive in several." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5779641" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5779641/files/figure.png" pageId="117" pageNumber="120">Figure 34</figureCitation>
). Several other fish also had meristic traits of 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FDB371B677228E20" baseAuthorityName="Lacepede" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[551,632,1530,1552]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigus">R. pigus</taxonomicName>
(&gt;43/44 lateral line scales), yet otherwise resembled 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FB0571B675C18E00" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilus">R. rutilus</taxonomicName>
. The mismatch between general appearance, meristic traits and mitochondrial barcode again indicates hybridisation and backcrossing between 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FE6C727677108E60" baseAuthorityName="Lacepede" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[504,586,1594,1616]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigus">R. pigus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FDE87276778C8E60" box="[636,726,1594,1616]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilus">R. rutilus</taxonomicName>
, and in Lake Maggiore also between the two native species R. aula and 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FEF7721674EF8E40" baseAuthorityName="Lacepede" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[355,437,1626,1648]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigus">R. pigus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</paragraph>
<subSubSection id="C32265489B5BBB22FFE472D776D58FE0" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8736C39B5BBB22FFE472D771C88F40" blockId="117.[112,1225,1690,1904]" pageId="117" pageNumber="120">
To our knowledge, this is the first genetic data that show that the dramatic decline of native 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FC6972D671148E80" baseAuthorityName="Lacepede" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[1021,1102,1690,1712]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pigus">R. pigus</taxonomicName>
and R. aula in Lakes Lugano and Maggiore was associated with introgression into the abundant invasive northern 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FBFC72F6719A8EE0" box="[1128,1216,1722,1744]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilus">R. rutilus</taxonomicName>
(as predicted in 
<superScript id="7C4D9B8B9B5BBB22FE81729574758ED7" attach="right" box="[277,303,1752,1767]" fontSize="6" pageId="117" pageNumber="120">[92]</superScript>
), but also with introgression between the two native species. It is possibly that the breakdown of reproductive isolation between the native species was mediated by the hyperabundant invasive species. Such complex species interactions deserve further attention by researchers. Another important line of research for the conservation of the native southern 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FDF4737777A38F60" box="[608,761,1850,1872]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">Rutilus species</taxonomicName>
would address the reasons for the dominance of the invasive 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FE93731774CA8F40" authority="rutilus" box="[263,400,1882,1904]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rutilus">Rutilus rutilus</taxonomicName>
in Lakes Lugano, Maggiore and Varese, but not in Lakes Como and Mezzola.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8736C39B5BBB22FFE473D776D58FE0" blockId="117.[112,1220,1946,2000]" pageId="117" pageNumber="120">
There was no evidence for translocation of either of the southern 
<taxonomicName id="4C384D409B5BBB22FC9B73D776F38F80" box="[783,937,1946,1968]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Rutilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="117" pageNumber="120" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">Rutilus species</taxonomicName>
to the lakes in the Rhine or Rhone catchments (several thousand phenotypes inspected, 70 fish barcoded).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
